# 🔹 What is Dynamic Programming (DP)?

Dynamic Programming is an algorithmic technique used to solve problems by:

1. Breaking a problem into **smaller overlapping subproblems**.
2. Solving each subproblem **only once**.
3. Storing the result and reusing it whenever needed.

📌 **Core Idea:** *Don't solve the same subproblem repeatedly.*

---

# 🔹 When to Use Dynamic Programming?

A problem is suitable for DP if it has:

### 1️⃣ Optimal Substructure

The optimal solution can be built from optimal solutions of smaller subproblems.

### 2️⃣ Overlapping Subproblems

The same subproblems occur multiple times.

Example:

Computing Fibonacci numbers recursively.

```text
F(5)
├── F(4)
│   ├── F(3)
│   └── F(2)
└── F(3)
```

Notice that **F(3)** is computed more than once.

---

# 🔹 Dynamic Programming vs Recursion

| Recursion              | Dynamic Programming |
| ---------------------- | ------------------- |
| Recomputes subproblems | Stores results      |
| Slower                 | Faster              |
| More repeated work     | No repeated work    |
| Higher execution time  | Optimized execution |

---

# 🔹 Memoization (Top-Down DP)

Memoization uses recursion + memory.

### Steps

1. Solve recursively.
2. Store computed answers.
3. Reuse stored values.

---

### Fibonacci Example

Without Memoization:

```text
F(5)
├── F(4)
├── F(3)
├── F(2)
...
```

Many repeated calls.

With Memoization:

Each Fibonacci value is computed **only once**.

---

## Complexity

Time:

[
O(n)
]

Space:

[
O(n)
]

---

# 🔹 Tabulation (Bottom-Up DP)

Instead of recursion:

1. Start from the smallest subproblem.
2. Build answers iteratively.

Example:

```text
F(0)=0
F(1)=1
F(2)=1
F(3)=2
F(4)=3
F(5)=5
```

---

## Complexity

Time:

[
O(n)
]

Space:

[
O(n)
]

---

# 🔹 Memoization vs Tabulation

| Feature        | Memoization     | Tabulation     |
| -------------- | --------------- | -------------- |
| Approach       | Top-Down        | Bottom-Up      |
| Uses Recursion | Yes             | No             |
| Stack Space    | Yes             | No             |
| Speed          | Slightly slower | Usually faster |

📌 Very common GATE theory question.

