# 🔹 Longest Common Subsequence (LCS)

### Definition

The **Longest Common Subsequence** of two strings is the longest sequence of characters that appears in both strings **in the same order**, but **not necessarily consecutively**.

---

### Example

String 1:

```text
ABCBDAB
```

String 2:

```text
BDCABA
```

One LCS is:

```text
BCBA
```

Length:

```text
4
```

---

## DP Recurrence

If last characters are equal:

[
LCS(i,j)=1+LCS(i-1,j-1)
]

Else:

[
LCS(i,j)=\max(LCS(i-1,j),LCS(i,j-1))
]

---

## Complexity

Time:

[
O(mn)
]

Space:

[
O(mn)
]

Where:

* m = length of first string
* n = length of second string

